<section id="fs-idp3947216">
<title>Gas Exchange across the Alveoli</title>
<para id="fs-idm166832800">In the body, oxygen is used by cells of the body’s tissues and carbon dioxide is produced as a waste product. The ratio of carbon dioxide production to oxygen consumption is the <emphasis>respiratory quotient (RQ)</emphasis>. RQ varies between 0.7 and 1.0. If just glucose were used to fuel the body, the RQ would equal one. One mole of carbon dioxide would be produced for every mole of oxygen consumed. Glucose, however, is not the only fuel for the body. Protein and fat are also used as fuels for the body. Because of this, less carbon dioxide is produced than oxygen is consumed and the RQ is, on average, about 0.7 for fat and about 0.8 for protein.</para>
<para id="fs-idp87370304">The RQ is used to calculate the partial pressure of oxygen in the alveolar spaces within the lung, the <emphasis>alveolar <m:math>
