<label/><title>Think About It</title>
<exercise id="fs-id1167066029674" class="unnumbered"><label/>
<problem id="fs-id1167065850596"><para id="fs-id1167065850598">How can a respiratory infection such as pneumonia affect the exchange of gases between the alveoli in the lungs and the capillaries surrounding them?</para></problem></exercise>
</note>
<note id="fs-id1167062511416" class="os-teacher">
<label>Teacher Support</label>
<para id="fs-id1167066021075">The question is an application of AP<sup>®</sup> Learning Objective 2.12 and Science Practice 1.4 because students are using the model of gas exchange across respiratory surface to analyze a situation qualitatively to determine factors that can disrupt homeostasis in the movement of molecules across membranes.</para>
</note>
</note>
<section id="fs-idp53463968" class="summary ost-reading-discard">
<title>Section Summary</title><para id="fs-idp28521840">The lungs can hold a large volume of air, but they are not usually filled to maximal capacity. Lung volume measurements include tidal volume, expiratory reserve volume, inspiratory reserve volume, and residual volume. The sum of these equals the total lung capacity. Gas movement into or out of the lungs is dependent on the pressure of the gas. Air is a mixture of gases; therefore, the partial pressure of each gas can be calculated to determine how the gas will flow in the lung. The difference between the partial pressure of the gas in the air drives oxygen into the tissues and carbon dioxide out of the body.</para>
</section>
